com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.order

Class MaterializingOrderedResultSet<O>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.ResultSet<O>
      • com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.order.MaterializingOrderedResultSet<O>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<O>

    public class MaterializingOrderedResultSet<O>
extends ResultSet<O>
    A ResultSet which wraps another ResultSet, providing an iterator() method which returns objects in sorted order according to a comparator supplied to the constructor of this ResultSet, and which never returns the same object more than once.

    This is implemented by copying objects from the wrapped ResultSet into a sorted set on-demand when the iterator() method is called, and then returning an iterator over that set.

    Insertion-sorting, and then iterating objects in this manner has O(merge_cost^2 * log(merge_cost)) time complexity. See the iterator() and getMergeCost() methods for details.

    Author:
    Niall Gallagher

      • size

        public int size()
        Returns the number of objects which would be returned by this ResultSet if iterated.

        Note that the cost of calling this method depends on the query for which it was constructed.

        For simple queries where a single query is supplied and a matching index exists, or where several such simple queries are supplied and are connected using a simple Or query, calculating the size via this method will be cheaper than iterating through the ResultSet and counting the number of objects individually.

        For more complex queries, where intersections must be performed or where no suitable indexes exist, calling this method can be non-trivial, but it will always be at least as cheap as iterating through the ResultSet and counting the number of objects individually.

        This implementation has O(merge_cost^2 * log(merge_cost)) time complexity, because it delegates to the iterator() method and counts objects returned.

        Specified by:
        size in class ResultSet<O>
        Returns:
        The number of objects which would be returned by this ResultSet if iterated
